04846nam a22007695i 9780801468155DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979747903  a97808014681557 a10.7591/97808014681552doi  a(DE-B1597)478416  a(OCoLC)828736812  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aRC488.5b.W45 2016 7aPSY0410002bisacsh04a616.891562231 aWeinstein, Deborah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Pathological Family :bPostwar America and the Rise of Family Therapy /cDeborah Weinstein. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b8 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in the History of Psychiatry00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Power of the Family -- t1. Personality Factories -- t2. “Systems Everywhere”: Schizophrenia, Cybernetics, and the Double Bind -- t3. The Culture Concept at Work -- t4. Observational Practices and Natural Habitats -- t5. Visions of Family Life -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile iconic popular images celebrated family life during the 1950s and 1960s, American families were simultaneously regarded as potentially menacing sources of social disruption. The history of family therapy makes the complicated power of the family at midcentury vividly apparent. Clinicians developed a new approach to psychotherapy that claimed to locate the cause and treatment of mental illness in observable patterns of family interaction and communication rather than in individual psyches. Drawing on cybernetics, systems theory, and the social and behavioral sciences, they ambitiously aimed to cure schizophrenia and stop juvenile delinquency. With particular sensitivity to the importance of scientific observation and visual technologies such as one-way mirrors and training films in shaping the young field, The Pathological Family examines how family therapy developed against the intellectual and cultural landscape of postwar America.As Deborah Weinstein shows, the midcentury expansion of America's therapeutic culture and the postwar fixation on family life profoundly affected one another. Family therapists and other postwar commentators alike framed the promotion of democracy in the language of personality formation and psychological health forged in the crucible of the family. As therapists in this era shifted their clinical gaze to whole families, they nevertheless grappled in particular with the role played by mothers in the onset of their children's aberrant behavior. Although attitudes toward family therapy have shifted during intervening generations, the relations between family and therapeutic culture remain salient today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCold WarxPsychological aspects. 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aFamilieszUnited StatesxPsychological aspects. 0aFamily psychotherapyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aGender Studies. 4aU.S. History. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Psychotherapy / Couples & Family.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146815540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801468155423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801468155/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL 